{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Since the equation is of first order, one may for example ask, whether given ρ ∈ L p, there is a solution π ∈ W 1,p.",
    "This was resolved affirmatively in the case d < p < ∞ by Ye [44].",
    "In the less regular regime of p < d, the Jacobian loses its geometric meaning and has very pathological behaviour.",
    "This can be seen in the work of Koumatos et al [29, 1.2].",
    "A particular special case of their result asserts that a Sobolev map π can be found which mapsQ = [0, 1] d to 2Q = [0, 2] d satisfying det Dπ = 1 in Q and π |∂Q = 2 Id.In fact, the map π may be required to lie in any Sobolev space W 1,p for p < d. This is a kind of infinitesimal analogue of the Banach-Tarski paradox, allowing one to double the global volume, while on the infinitesimal scale the volume stays preserved."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
